</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Coronary artery fistulas (CAFs) are abnormal communications of coronary arteries whereby venous circuits bypass the normal capillaries within the myocardium. CAFs are rare, and most affected patients are asymptomatic. However, these fistulas are the most common coronary artery anomalies that can alter coronary hemodynamic parameters. Although most CAFs are asymptomatic in young patients, symptoms and complications become more frequent with increasing age. CAFs are characterized by variable clinical manifestations that are based on the size, origin, and drainage site of the fistula. In symptomatic cases, surgical ligation or percutaneous transcatheter closure is often recommended. Although CAFs historically have been evaluated with conventional invasive angiography, electrocardiographically gated cardiac computed tomographic (CT) angiography has emerged as the noninvasive alternative modality of choice owing to the high spatial and temporal resolution and short acquisition time. Furthermore, three-dimensional volume-rendered CT angiograms facilitate accurate assessment of the complex anatomy of CAFs, including their origin, drainage site, and complexity and the number and size of fistulous tracts. Knowledge of these characteristics is crucial for therapeutic planning. Radiologists must be aware of the pathophysiology, clinical manifestations, and characteristic CT angiographic findings of CAFs; appropriate CT angiographic protocols for evaluation of various CAFs; and the role of CT angiography in preprocedural planning and follow-up.</div><div role="paragraph"><i>Online supplemental material is available for this article.</i></div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2018</div><div role="paragraph"><b>An earlier incorrect version appeared online. This article was corrected on October 16, 2018.</b></div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2018170158">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2018170158">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig1.jpeg" height="1456" width="2500" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Classification of CAFs based on drainage site. The following fistula types are illustrated: <i>A,</i> Coronary cameral fistula involving the right ventricle chamber); <i>B,</i> coronary cameral fistula involving the right atrium chamber; <i>C,</i> coronary artery–to–pulmonary artery fistula involving a single large fistulous tract; <i>D,</i> coronary artery–to–pulmonary artery fistula involving multiple small fistulous tracts; <i>E,</i> coronary artery–to–coronary sinus fistula; <i>F,</i> coronary artery–to–cardiac vein fistula; and, <i>G,</i> coronary artery–to–bronchial artery fistula. <a href="#fig1">Figure 1,C and D</a>, adapted and reprinted, with permission, from reference 41.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig2a.jpeg" height="964" width="1078" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. Coronary cameral fistula in a 42-year-old man with a heart murmur. <b>(a, b)</b> Volume-rendered CT images obtained at different levels show a diffusely dilated RCA (white arrow) along the arterioventricular groove and draining into the left ventricle chamber (black arrow in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Curved multiplanar reformatted CT image depicts a fistulous communication between the dilated RCA (white arrow) and the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i> chamber (black arrow). The left ventricle hypertrophy (arrowheads) is due to increased blood volume in the left cardiac chamber.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig2b.jpeg" height="964" width="1117" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. Coronary cameral fistula in a 42-year-old man with a heart murmur. <b>(a, b)</b> Volume-rendered CT images obtained at different levels show a diffusely dilated RCA (white arrow) along the arterioventricular groove and draining into the left ventricle chamber (black arrow in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Curved multiplanar reformatted CT image depicts a fistulous communication between the dilated RCA (white arrow) and the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i> chamber (black arrow). The left ventricle hypertrophy (arrowheads) is due to increased blood volume in the left cardiac chamber.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig2c.jpeg" height="964" width="1502" aria-labelledby="fig2c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2c</span>. Coronary cameral fistula in a 42-year-old man with a heart murmur. <b>(a, b)</b> Volume-rendered CT images obtained at different levels show a diffusely dilated RCA (white arrow) along the arterioventricular groove and draining into the left ventricle chamber (black arrow in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Curved multiplanar reformatted CT image depicts a fistulous communication between the dilated RCA (white arrow) and the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i> chamber (black arrow). The left ventricle hypertrophy (arrowheads) is due to increased blood volume in the left cardiac chamber.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig2c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig3a.jpeg" height="1122" width="1004" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Coronary cameral fistula in a 55-year-old man. <b>(a–c)</b> Volume-rendered CT images obtained at different levels show a diffusely dilated obtuse marginal branch (arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) draining into the left ventricle chamber (arrow in <b>c</b>). <b>(d)</b> Curved multiplanar reformatted CT image depicts a fistulous communication between the dilated obtuse marginal branch (white arrows) and the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i> chamber (black arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig3b.jpeg" height="1121" width="1338" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Coronary cameral fistula in a 55-year-old man. <b>(a–c)</b> Volume-rendered CT images obtained at different levels show a diffusely dilated obtuse marginal branch (arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) draining into the left ventricle chamber (arrow in <b>c</b>). <b>(d)</b> Curved multiplanar reformatted CT image depicts a fistulous communication between the dilated obtuse marginal branch (white arrows) and the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i> chamber (black arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig3c.jpeg" height="1121" width="1356" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span>. Coronary cameral fistula in a 55-year-old man. <b>(a–c)</b> Volume-rendered CT images obtained at different levels show a diffusely dilated obtuse marginal branch (arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) draining into the left ventricle chamber (arrow in <b>c</b>). <b>(d)</b> Curved multiplanar reformatted CT image depicts a fistulous communication between the dilated obtuse marginal branch (white arrows) and the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i> chamber (black arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig3d.jpeg" height="739" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig3d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3d</span>. Coronary cameral fistula in a 55-year-old man. <b>(a–c)</b> Volume-rendered CT images obtained at different levels show a diffusely dilated obtuse marginal branch (arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) draining into the left ventricle chamber (arrow in <b>c</b>). <b>(d)</b> Curved multiplanar reformatted CT image depicts a fistulous communication between the dilated obtuse marginal branch (white arrows) and the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i> chamber (black arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig3d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig4a.jpeg" height="1291" width="1326" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Coronary cameral fistula in a 63-year-old man who presented with dyspnea. <b>(a, b)</b> Volume-rendered CT images obtained at different levels show a dilated and calcified LAD (closed arrows) coursing along the anterior and posterior interventricular grooves into the right ventricle chamber (open arrow in <b>b</b>), representing a left-to-right shunt. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial CT images show a coronary cameral fistula originating from the dilated LAD (arrow in <b>c</b>) and draining into the right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> chamber (arrow in <b>d</b>). Note the bulbous change in the fistulous tract at the entrance to the right ventricle chamber. <b>(e)</b> Curved multiplanar reformatted CT image shows a fistulous communication between the dilated LAD (arrow) and the right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> chamber. (Images courtesy of Whal Lee, MD, PhD, and Eun-Ah Park, MD, PhD, Seoul National University Hospital, Seoul, Republic of Korea.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig4b.jpeg" height="1291" width="1321" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Coronary cameral fistula in a 63-year-old man who presented with dyspnea. <b>(a, b)</b> Volume-rendered CT images obtained at different levels show a dilated and calcified LAD (closed arrows) coursing along the anterior and posterior interventricular grooves into the right ventricle chamber (open arrow in <b>b</b>), representing a left-to-right shunt. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial CT images show a coronary cameral fistula originating from the dilated LAD (arrow in <b>c</b>) and draining into the right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> chamber (arrow in <b>d</b>). Note the bulbous change in the fistulous tract at the entrance to the right ventricle chamber. <b>(e)</b> Curved multiplanar reformatted CT image shows a fistulous communication between the dilated LAD (arrow) and the right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> chamber. (Images courtesy of Whal Lee, MD, PhD, and Eun-Ah Park, MD, PhD, Seoul National University Hospital, Seoul, Republic of Korea.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig4c.jpeg" height="1363" width="1269" aria-labelledby="fig4c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span>. Coronary cameral fistula in a 63-year-old man who presented with dyspnea. <b>(a, b)</b> Volume-rendered CT images obtained at different levels show a dilated and calcified LAD (closed arrows) coursing along the anterior and posterior interventricular grooves into the right ventricle chamber (open arrow in <b>b</b>), representing a left-to-right shunt. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial CT images show a coronary cameral fistula originating from the dilated LAD (arrow in <b>c</b>) and draining into the right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> chamber (arrow in <b>d</b>). Note the bulbous change in the fistulous tract at the entrance to the right ventricle chamber. <b>(e)</b> Curved multiplanar reformatted CT image shows a fistulous communication between the dilated LAD (arrow) and the right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> chamber. (Images courtesy of Whal Lee, MD, PhD, and Eun-Ah Park, MD, PhD, Seoul National University Hospital, Seoul, Republic of Korea.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig4c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig4d.jpeg" height="1363" width="1514" aria-labelledby="fig4d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4d</span>. Coronary cameral fistula in a 63-year-old man who presented with dyspnea. <b>(a, b)</b> Volume-rendered CT images obtained at different levels show a dilated and calcified LAD (closed arrows) coursing along the anterior and posterior interventricular grooves into the right ventricle chamber (open arrow in <b>b</b>), representing a left-to-right shunt. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial CT images show a coronary cameral fistula originating from the dilated LAD (arrow in <b>c</b>) and draining into the right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> chamber (arrow in <b>d</b>). Note the bulbous change in the fistulous tract at the entrance to the right ventricle chamber. <b>(e)</b> Curved multiplanar reformatted CT image shows a fistulous communication between the dilated LAD (arrow) and the right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> chamber. (Images courtesy of Whal Lee, MD, PhD, and Eun-Ah Park, MD, PhD, Seoul National University Hospital, Seoul, Republic of Korea.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig4d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig4e.jpeg" height="1363" width="909" aria-labelledby="fig4e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4e</span>. Coronary cameral fistula in a 63-year-old man who presented with dyspnea. <b>(a, b)</b> Volume-rendered CT images obtained at different levels show a dilated and calcified LAD (closed arrows) coursing along the anterior and posterior interventricular grooves into the right ventricle chamber (open arrow in <b>b</b>), representing a left-to-right shunt. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial CT images show a coronary cameral fistula originating from the dilated LAD (arrow in <b>c</b>) and draining into the right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> chamber (arrow in <b>d</b>). Note the bulbous change in the fistulous tract at the entrance to the right ventricle chamber. <b>(e)</b> Curved multiplanar reformatted CT image shows a fistulous communication between the dilated LAD (arrow) and the right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> chamber. (Images courtesy of Whal Lee, MD, PhD, and Eun-Ah Park, MD, PhD, Seoul National University Hospital, Seoul, Republic of Korea.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig4e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig5a.jpeg" height="1415" width="1090" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. Coronary-to-pulmonary artery fistula in a 55-year-old man with dyspnea. <b>(a, b)</b> Volume-rendered CT images obtained at different levels show a single prominent fistulous connection from the conus branch of the LAD (solid arrow) into the main pulmonary trunk (open arrow in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Invasive coronary angiogram findings confirm the presence of a coronary-to-pulmonary artery fistula, with a single prominent tract, originating from the proximal LAD (solid arrow) and draining into the main pulmonary trunk (open arrow). Note the focal aneurysmal change in the fistulous tract (arrowhead in <b>a</b> and <b>c</b>). (Also see Movie 1.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig5b.jpeg" height="1415" width="1263" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. Coronary-to-pulmonary artery fistula in a 55-year-old man with dyspnea. <b>(a, b)</b> Volume-rendered CT images obtained at different levels show a single prominent fistulous connection from the conus branch of the LAD (solid arrow) into the main pulmonary trunk (open arrow in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Invasive coronary angiogram findings confirm the presence of a coronary-to-pulmonary artery fistula, with a single prominent tract, originating from the proximal LAD (solid arrow) and draining into the main pulmonary trunk (open arrow). Note the focal aneurysmal change in the fistulous tract (arrowhead in <b>a</b> and <b>c</b>). (Also see Movie 1.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig5c.jpeg" height="1415" width="1352" aria-labelledby="fig5c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span>. Coronary-to-pulmonary artery fistula in a 55-year-old man with dyspnea. <b>(a, b)</b> Volume-rendered CT images obtained at different levels show a single prominent fistulous connection from the conus branch of the LAD (solid arrow) into the main pulmonary trunk (open arrow in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Invasive coronary angiogram findings confirm the presence of a coronary-to-pulmonary artery fistula, with a single prominent tract, originating from the proximal LAD (solid arrow) and draining into the main pulmonary trunk (open arrow). Note the focal aneurysmal change in the fistulous tract (arrowhead in <b>a</b> and <b>c</b>). (Also see Movie 1.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig5c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig6a.jpeg" height="908" width="1309" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Coronary-to-pulmonary artery fistula in a 62-year-old man who underwent percutaneous coil embolization. <b>(a–f)</b> CT images were obtained before coil embolization. Axial CT images <b>(a, b)</b> show multiple dilated fistulous connections arising and a tortuous fistulous tract arising from the conus branches of the RCA (<i>CB_R</i>) and LAD (<i>CB_L</i>) (arrows in <b>b</b>) into the main pulmonary trunk (arrows in <b>a</b>). Two-chamber reformatted CT image <b>(c)</b> shows the contrast shunt sign (ie, contrast blush) created as a jet of contrast material flushes into the relatively less-opacified pulmonary artery (arrow). Volume-rendered CT image <b>(d)</b> and invasive coronary angiograms <b>(e, f)</b> show the Vieussens ring (arrowheads in <b>d</b> and <b>e</b>), composed of the conus branches of the LAD (<i>CB_L</i>) and RCA (<i>CB_R</i>) (solid arrows), along the prepulmonary trunk. In this case, the CAFs are originating from two vessels: a 3-mm conus branch of the RCA and a 3-mm conus branch of the LAD. The drainage site is the main pulmonary trunk (open arrows), and the fistulous tract course is the prepulmonary trunk, anterior to the right ventricular outflow tract. No accompanying cardiac abnormalities are seen. <b>(g–i)</b> Axial CT image <b>(g)</b>, volume-rendered CT image <b>(h)</b>, and invasive coronary angiogram <b>(i)</b> obtained after successful embolization with use of coils show no residual fistula. The fistula tract is completely obliterated, with no evidence of recanalization, persistent coronary artery dilatation, or thrombus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig6b.jpeg" height="908" width="1324" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Coronary-to-pulmonary artery fistula in a 62-year-old man who underwent percutaneous coil embolization. <b>(a–f)</b> CT images were obtained before coil embolization. Axial CT images <b>(a, b)</b> show multiple dilated fistulous connections arising and a tortuous fistulous tract arising from the conus branches of the RCA (<i>CB_R</i>) and LAD (<i>CB_L</i>) (arrows in <b>b</b>) into the main pulmonary trunk (arrows in <b>a</b>). Two-chamber reformatted CT image <b>(c)</b> shows the contrast shunt sign (ie, contrast blush) created as a jet of contrast material flushes into the relatively less-opacified pulmonary artery (arrow). Volume-rendered CT image <b>(d)</b> and invasive coronary angiograms <b>(e, f)</b> show the Vieussens ring (arrowheads in <b>d</b> and <b>e</b>), composed of the conus branches of the LAD (<i>CB_L</i>) and RCA (<i>CB_R</i>) (solid arrows), along the prepulmonary trunk. In this case, the CAFs are originating from two vessels: a 3-mm conus branch of the RCA and a 3-mm conus branch of the LAD. The drainage site is the main pulmonary trunk (open arrows), and the fistulous tract course is the prepulmonary trunk, anterior to the right ventricular outflow tract. No accompanying cardiac abnormalities are seen. <b>(g–i)</b> Axial CT image <b>(g)</b>, volume-rendered CT image <b>(h)</b>, and invasive coronary angiogram <b>(i)</b> obtained after successful embolization with use of coils show no residual fistula. The fistula tract is completely obliterated, with no evidence of recanalization, persistent coronary artery dilatation, or thrombus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig6c.jpeg" height="908" width="1065" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span>. Coronary-to-pulmonary artery fistula in a 62-year-old man who underwent percutaneous coil embolization. <b>(a–f)</b> CT images were obtained before coil embolization. Axial CT images <b>(a, b)</b> show multiple dilated fistulous connections arising and a tortuous fistulous tract arising from the conus branches of the RCA (<i>CB_R</i>) and LAD (<i>CB_L</i>) (arrows in <b>b</b>) into the main pulmonary trunk (arrows in <b>a</b>). Two-chamber reformatted CT image <b>(c)</b> shows the contrast shunt sign (ie, contrast blush) created as a jet of contrast material flushes into the relatively less-opacified pulmonary artery (arrow). Volume-rendered CT image <b>(d)</b> and invasive coronary angiograms <b>(e, f)</b> show the Vieussens ring (arrowheads in <b>d</b> and <b>e</b>), composed of the conus branches of the LAD (<i>CB_L</i>) and RCA (<i>CB_R</i>) (solid arrows), along the prepulmonary trunk. In this case, the CAFs are originating from two vessels: a 3-mm conus branch of the RCA and a 3-mm conus branch of the LAD. The drainage site is the main pulmonary trunk (open arrows), and the fistulous tract course is the prepulmonary trunk, anterior to the right ventricular outflow tract. No accompanying cardiac abnormalities are seen. <b>(g–i)</b> Axial CT image <b>(g)</b>, volume-rendered CT image <b>(h)</b>, and invasive coronary angiogram <b>(i)</b> obtained after successful embolization with use of coils show no residual fistula. The fistula tract is completely obliterated, with no evidence of recanalization, persistent coronary artery dilatation, or thrombus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig6d.jpeg" heig