s="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig6h">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6i" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig6i.jpeg" height="1306" width="1372" aria-labelledby="fig6i" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6i</span>. Coronary-to-pulmonary artery fistula in a 62-year-old man who underwent percutaneous coil embolization. <b>(a–f)</b> CT images were obtained before coil embolization. Axial CT images <b>(a, b)</b> show multiple dilated fistulous connections arising and a tortuous fistulous tract arising from the conus branches of the RCA (<i>CB_R</i>) and LAD (<i>CB_L</i>) (arrows in <b>b</b>) into the main pulmonary trunk (arrows in <b>a</b>). Two-chamber reformatted CT image <b>(c)</b> shows the contrast shunt sign (ie, contrast blush) created as a jet of contrast material flushes into the relatively less-opacified pulmonary artery (arrow). Volume-rendered CT image <b>(d)</b> and invasive coronary angiograms <b>(e, f)</b> show the Vieussens ring (arrowheads in <b>d</b> and <b>e</b>), composed of the conus branches of the LAD (<i>CB_L</i>) and RCA (<i>CB_R</i>) (solid arrows), along the prepulmonary trunk. In this case, the CAFs are originating from two vessels: a 3-mm conus branch of the RCA and a 3-mm conus branch of the LAD. The drainage site is the main pulmonary trunk (open arrows), and the fistulous tract course is the prepulmonary trunk, anterior to the right ventricular outflow tract. No accompanying cardiac abnormalities are seen. <b>(g–i)</b> Axial CT image <b>(g)</b>, volume-rendered CT image <b>(h)</b>, and invasive coronary angiogram <b>(i)</b> obtained after successful embolization with use of coils show no residual fistula. The fistula tract is completely obliterated, with no evidence of recanalization, persistent coronary artery dilatation, or thrombus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig6i">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig7a.jpeg" height="1034" width="1491" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Coronary artery–to–cardiac vein fistula in a 57-year-old woman with chest pain. <b>(a, b)</b> Volume-rendered CT images obtained at different levels show tortuous first <i>(D1)</i> and second <i>(D2)</i> diagonal branches of the LAD (solid arrows) connected to a dilated middle cardiac vein <i>(MCV)</i> (open arrows), which drains into the coronary sinus <i>(CS).</i> Arrowheads point to connecting points between the first or second diagonal branch of the LAD and the middle cardiac vein.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig7b.jpeg" height="1034" width="1351" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Coronary artery–to–cardiac vein fistula in a 57-year-old woman with chest pain. <b>(a, b)</b> Volume-rendered CT images obtained at different levels show tortuous first <i>(D1)</i> and second <i>(D2)</i> diagonal branches of the LAD (solid arrows) connected to a dilated middle cardiac vein <i>(MCV)</i> (open arrows), which drains into the coronary sinus <i>(CS).</i> Arrowheads point to connecting points between the first or second diagonal branch of the LAD and the middle cardiac vein.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig8a.jpeg" height="1033" width="864" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Coronary artery–to–cardiac vein fistula in a 51-year-old woman with exertional dyspnea. <b>(a–c)</b> Serial axial CT images show a dilated tortuous posterior descending artery (PDA) branch from the RCA (long arrow) along the posterior interventricular groove, draining into the middle cardiac vein (short arrows in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>). Arrowheads in <b>c</b> point to the connecting point between the PDA branch and middle cardiac vein. <b>(d)</b> Volume-rendered CT image also shows the fistulous connection between the dilated tortuous PDA branch of the RCA (solid arrows) and the middle cardiac vein (open arrows); <b>*</b> indicates the connecting point. (Images provided courtesy of Whal Lee, MD, PhD, and Eun-Ah Park, MD, PhD, Seoul National University Hospital, Seoul, Republic of Korea.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig8b.jpeg" height="1119" width="975" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Coronary artery–to–cardiac vein fistula in a 51-year-old woman with exertional dyspnea. <b>(a–c)</b> Serial axial CT images show a dilated tortuous posterior descending artery (PDA) branch from the RCA (long arrow) along the posterior interventricular groove, draining into the middle cardiac vein (short arrows in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>). Arrowheads in <b>c</b> point to the connecting point between the PDA branch and middle cardiac vein. <b>(d)</b> Volume-rendered CT image also shows the fistulous connection between the dilated tortuous PDA branch of the RCA (solid arrows) and the middle cardiac vein (open arrows); <b>*</b> indicates the connecting point. (Images provided courtesy of Whal Lee, MD, PhD, and Eun-Ah Park, MD, PhD, Seoul National University Hospital, Seoul, Republic of Korea.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig8c.jpeg" height="1119" width="1051" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span>. Coronary artery–to–cardiac vein fistula in a 51-year-old woman with exertional dyspnea. <b>(a–c)</b> Serial axial CT images show a dilated tortuous posterior descending artery (PDA) branch from the RCA (long arrow) along the posterior interventricular groove, draining into the middle cardiac vein (short arrows in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>). Arrowheads in <b>c</b> point to the connecting point between the PDA branch and middle cardiac vein. <b>(d)</b> Volume-rendered CT image also shows the fistulous connection between the dilated tortuous PDA branch of the RCA (solid arrows) and the middle cardiac vein (open arrows); <b>*</b> indicates the connecting point. (Images provided courtesy of Whal Lee, MD, PhD, and Eun-Ah Park, MD, PhD, Seoul National University Hospital, Seoul, Republic of Korea.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig8d.jpeg" height="1119" width="1069" aria-labelledby="fig8d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8d</span>. Coronary artery–to–cardiac vein fistula in a 51-year-old woman with exertional dyspnea. <b>(a–c)</b> Serial axial CT images show a dilated tortuous posterior descending artery (PDA) branch from the RCA (long arrow) along the posterior interventricular groove, draining into the middle cardiac vein (short arrows in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>). Arrowheads in <b>c</b> point to the connecting point between the PDA branch and middle cardiac vein. <b>(d)</b> Volume-rendered CT image also shows the fistulous connection between the dilated tortuous PDA branch of the RCA (solid arrows) and the middle cardiac vein (open arrows); <b>*</b> indicates the connecting point. (Images provided courtesy of Whal Lee, MD, PhD, and Eun-Ah Park, MD, PhD, Seoul National University Hospital, Seoul, Republic of Korea.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig8d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig9a.jpeg" height="1118" width="1001" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Coronary-to-bronchial artery fistula in a 60-year-old man with atrial fibrillation and an intermittent cough. <b>(a, b)</b> Volume-rendered CT images obtained at different levels show a branch of the left main coronary artery along the anterior aspect of the pulmonary artery (solid arrows). This branch continues with the bronchial arteries arising from the descending thoracic aorta <i>(DTA)</i> (open arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial lung-window CT image shows cystic bronchiectasis in the left lower lobe. (Also see Movie 2.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig9b.jpeg" height="1404" width="1000" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Coronary-to-bronchial artery fistula in a 60-year-old man with atrial fibrillation and an intermittent cough. <b>(a, b)</b> Volume-rendered CT images obtained at different levels show a branch of the left main coronary artery along the anterior aspect of the pulmonary artery (solid arrows). This branch continues with the bronchial arteries arising from the descending thoracic aorta <i>(DTA)</i> (open arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial lung-window CT image shows cystic bronchiectasis in the left lower lobe. (Also see Movie 2.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig9c.jpeg" height="1507" width="1808" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span>. Coronary-to-bronchial artery fistula in a 60-year-old man with atrial fibrillation and an intermittent cough. <b>(a, b)</b> Volume-rendered CT images obtained at different levels show a branch of the left main coronary artery along the anterior aspect of the pulmonary artery (solid arrows). This branch continues with the bronchial arteries arising from the descending thoracic aorta <i>(DTA)</i> (open arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial lung-window CT image shows cystic bronchiectasis in the left lower lobe. (Also see Movie 2.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig10.jpeg" height="1153" width="1183" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span>. Complex CAF in a 48-year-old man with mild dyspnea. Volume-rendered CT image shows tortuous diagonal branches of the LAD <i>(D1)</i> connected to a dilated winding pericardiophrenic artery (white arrow) derived from the internal mammary artery <i>(IMA),</i> which is also connected to the inferior phrenic artery <i>(IPA)</i> arising from the thoracic aorta. The pericardiophrenic artery is also continuous with the left marginal vein <i>(LMV)</i> (long black arrows), which drains into the great cardiac vein <i>(GCV)</i> (short black arrow), creating the network of vessels entangled with multiple fistulous tracts (arrowheads). (Also see Movie 3.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig11a.jpeg" height="1428" width="1411" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Coronary cameral fistula with a proximal thrombosed RCA aneurysm in a 39-year-old woman who subsequently underwent surgical ligation. <b>(a, b)</b> Preprocedural axial <b>(a)</b> and volume-rendered <b>(b)</b> CT images show a dilated RCA (solid arrow), which drains into the right atrium <i>(RA)</i> chamber (open arrow). Note the thrombus (<b>*</b> in <b>a</b>) in the right atrium chamber, adjacent to a dilated fistulous tract from the RCA. In this case, the CAF has a single fistulous tract of large diameter (1 cm). The fistulous tract passes through the right atrioventricular groove and drains into the anterior surface of the right atrium. <b>(c, d)</b> On postprocedural axial <b>(c)</b> and volume-rendered <b>(d)</b> CT images, there is no visualization of the residual fistulous tract between the RCA and right atrium chamber owing to successful ligation of the proximal dilated RCA. The solid arrow indicates surgical clips. The fistula tract is completely obliterated at the proximal portion, without evidence of recanalization or persistent coronary artery dilatation. However, a residual thrombosed aneurysm is noted at the stumped portion of the fistulous tract in the right atrium (open arrow in <b>c</b>). (Also see Movie 4.) (Images provided courtesy of Whal Lee, MD, PhD, and Eun-Ah Park, MD, PhD, Seoul National University Hospital, Seoul, Republic of Korea.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig11b.jpeg" height="1428" width="1238" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Coronary cameral fistula with a proximal thrombosed RCA aneurysm in a 39-year-old woman who subsequently underwent surgical ligation. <b>(a, b)</b> Preprocedural axial <b>(a)</b> and volume-rendered <b>(b)</b> CT images show a dilated RCA (solid arrow), which drains into the right atrium <i>(RA)</i> chamber (open arrow). Note the thrombus (<b>*</b> in <b>a</b>) in the right atrium chamber, adjacent to a dilated fistulous tract from the RCA. In this case, the CAF has a single fistulous tract of large diameter (1 cm). The fistulous tract passes through the right atrioventricular groove and drains into the anterior surface of the right atrium. <b>(c, d)</b> On postprocedural axial <b>(c)</b> and volume-rendered <b>(d)</b> CT images, there is no visualization of the residual fistulous tract between the RCA and right atrium chamber owing to successful ligation of the proximal dilated RCA. The solid arrow indicates surgical clips. The fistula tract is completely obliterated at the proximal portion, without evidence of recanalization or persistent coronary artery dilatation. However, a residual thrombosed aneurysm is noted at the stumped portion of the fistulous tract in the right atrium (open arrow in <b>c</b>). (Also see Movie 4.) (Images provided courtesy of Whal Lee, MD, PhD, and Eun-Ah Park, MD, PhD, Seoul National University Hospital, Seoul, Republic of Korea.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig11c.jpeg" height="1379" width="1419" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span>. Coronary cameral fistula with a proximal thrombosed RCA aneurysm in a 39-year-old woman who subsequently underwent surgical ligation. <b>(a, b)</b> Preprocedural axial <b>(a)</b> and volume-rendered <b>(b)</b> CT images show a dilated RCA (solid arrow), which drains into the right atrium <i>(RA)</i> chamber (open arrow). Note the thrombus (<b>*</b> in <b>a</b>) in the right atrium chamber, adjacent to a dilated fistulous tract from the RCA. In this case, the CAF has a single fistulous tract of large diameter (1 cm). The fistulous tract passes through the right atrioventricular groove and drains into the anterior surface of the right atrium. <b>(c, d)</b> On postprocedural axial <b>(c)</b> and volume-rendered <b>(d)</b> CT images, there is no visualization of the residual fistulous tract between the RCA and right atrium chamber owing to successful ligation of the proximal dilated RCA. The solid arrow indicates surgical clips. The fistula tract is completely obliterated at the proximal portion, without evidence of recanalization or persistent coronary artery dilatation. However, a residual thrombosed aneurysm is noted at the stumped portion of the fistulous tract in the right atrium (open arrow in <b>c</b>). (Also see Movie 4.) (Images provided courtesy of Whal Lee, MD, PhD, and Eun-Ah Park, MD, PhD, Seoul National University Hospital, Seoul, Republic of Korea.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170158/asset/images/large/rg.2018170158.fig11d.jpeg" height="1379" width="1228" aria-labelledby="fig11d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11d</span>. Coronary cameral fistula with a proximal thrombosed RCA aneurysm in a 39-year-old woman who subsequently underwent surgical ligation. <b>(a, b)</b> Preprocedural axial <b>(a)</b> and volume-rendered <b>(b)</b> CT images show a dilated RCA (solid arrow), which drains into the right atrium <i>(RA)</i> chamber (open arrow). Note the thrombus (<b>*</b> in <b>a</b>) in the right atrium chamber, adjacent to a dilated fistulous tract from the RCA. In this case, the CAF has a single fistulous tract of large diameter (1 cm). The fistulous tract passes through the right atrioventricular groove and drains into the anterior surface of the right atrium. <b>(c, d)</b> On postprocedural axial <b>(c)</b> and volume-rendered <b>(d)</b> CT images, there is no visualization of the residual fistulous tract between the RCA and right atrium chamber owing to successful ligation of the proximal dilated RCA. The solid arrow indicates surgical clips. The fistula tract is completely obliterated at the proximal portion, without evidence of recanalization or persistent coronary artery dilatation. However, a residual thrombosed aneurysm is noted at the stumped portion of the fistulous tract in the right atrium (open arrow in <b>c</b>). (Also see Movie 4.) (Images provided courtesy of Whal Lee, MD, PhD, and Eun-Ah Park, MD, PhD, Seoul National University Hospital, Seoul, Republic of Korea.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170158&amp;id=fig11d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">McNamara JJ, Gross RE. Congenital coronary artery fistula. <em>Surgery</em> 1969;65(1):59–69.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/5762418/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Congenital+coronary+artery+fistula&amp;author=JJ+McNamara&amp;author=RE+Gross&amp;publication_year=1969&amp;journal=Surgery&amp;pages=59-69&amp;pmid=5762418">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Vavuranakis M, Bush CA, Boudoulas H. Coronary artery fistulas in adults: incidence, angiographic characteristics, natural history. <em>Cathet Cardiovasc Diagn</em> 1995;35(2):116–120.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1002/ccd.1810350207">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/7656302/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Coronary+artery+fistulas+in+adults%3A+incidence%2C+angiographic+characteristics%2C+natural+history&amp;author=M+Vavuranakis&amp;author=CA+Bush&amp;author=H+Boudoulas&amp;publication_year=1995&amp;journal=Cathet+Cardiovasc+Diagn&amp;pages=116-120&amp;doi=10.1002%2Fccd.1810350207&amp;pmid=7656302">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">3.</div><div id="r3" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Yamanaka O, Hobbs RE. Coronary artery anomalies in 126,595 patients undergoing coronary arteriography. <em>Cathet Cardiovasc Diagn</em> 1990;21(1):28–40.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1002/ccd.1810210110">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/2208265/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Coronary+artery+anomalies+in+126%2C595+patients+undergoing+coronary+arteriography&amp;author=O+Yamanaka&amp;author=RE+Hobbs&amp;publication_year=1990&amp;journal=Cathet+Cardiovasc+Diagn&amp;pages=28-40&amp;doi=10.1002%2Fccd.1810210110&amp;pmid=2208265">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">4.</div><div id="r4" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Kim MS, Jung JI, Chun HJ. Coronary to pulmonary artery fistula: morphologic features at multidetector CT. <em>Int J Cardiovasc Imaging</em> 2010;26(suppl 2):273–280.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/s10554-010-9711-3">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20878252/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Coronary+to+pulmonary+artery+fistula%3A+morphologic+features+at+multidetector+CT&amp;author=MS+Kim&amp;author=JI+Jung&amp;author=HJ+Chun&amp;publication_year=2010&amp;journal=Int+J+Cardiovasc+Imaging&amp;pages=273-280&amp;doi=10.1007%2Fs10554-010-9711-3&amp;pmid=20878252">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">5.</div><div id="r5" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Lim JJ, Jung JI, Lee BY, Lee HG. Prevalence and types of coronary artery fistulas detected with coronary CT angiography. <em>AJR Am J Roentgenol</em> 2014;203(3):W237–W243.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.2214/AJR.13.11613">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25148179/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Prevalence+and+types+of+coronary+artery+fistulas+detected+with+coronary+CT+angiography&amp;author=JJ+Lim&amp;author=JI+Jung&amp;author=BY+Lee&amp;author=HG+Lee&amp;publication_year=2014&amp;journal=AJR+Am+J+Roentgenol&amp;pages=W237-W243&amp;doi=10.2214%2FAJR.13.11613&amp;pmid=25148179">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">6.</div><div id="r6" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Vitarelli A, De Curtis G, Conde Y, et al. Assessment of congenital coronary artery fistulas by transesophageal color Doppler echocardiography. <em>Am J Med</em> 2002;113(2):127–133.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/S0002-9343(02)01157-9">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12133751/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Assessment+of+congenital+coronary+artery+fistulas+by+transesophageal+color+Doppler+echocardiography&amp;author=A+Vitarelli&amp;author=G+De+Curtis&amp;author=Y+Conde&amp;publication_year=2002&amp;journal=Am+J+Med&amp;pages=127-133&amp;doi=10.1016%2FS0002-9343%2802%2901157-9&amp;pmid=12133751">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">7.</div><div id="r7" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Krause W. Uber den ursprung einer accessorischen a. coronaria aus der a. pulmonalis. <em>Z Ratl Med</em> 1865;24:225–227.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Uber+den+ursprung+einer+accessorischen+a.+coronaria+aus+der+a.+pulmonalis&amp;author=W+Krause&amp;publication_year=1865&amp;journal=Z+Ratl+Med&amp;pages=225-227">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">8.</div><div id="r8" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Haller JA Jr, Little JA. Diagnosis and surgical correction of congenital coronary artery-coronary sinus fistula. <em>Circulation</em> 1963;27(5):939–942.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1161/01.CIR.27.5.939">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/13963552/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Diagnosis+and+surgical+correction+of+congenital+coronary+artery-coronary+sinus+fistula&amp;author=JA+Haller&amp;author=JA